␀␀   UNIXSOCKET - true (match or 1) if connection was over a UNIX a 4␀␀␀␀ ␀␀  permission tags now have the indicated values  rA␀␀␀␀␀␀  and a couple of new fields have been added.  The following␀␀K␀␀␀␀␀␀  checking is now recorded so it can be used for permissions checking.C␀␀␀␀␀␀ The authentication and connection information for permissions␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀5␀␀␀␀␀␀   (Patch from: Tobias Burnus <burnus@net-b.de>)esD␀␀␀␀␀␀   configure --enable-tcpwrappers     use tcp wrappers (-lwrap)s tF␀␀␀␀␀␀ Added patch to allow tcp wrappers to be used.  Configure updated␀␀␀␀␀␀␀   integer casts9␀␀␀␀␀␀␀      - also fixed up &*)*(&)*(& unsigned and signedrk'␀␀␀␀␀␀   -Wall -Werror -Wno-unused-parmsE␀␀␀␀␀␀   - added configure ability to find 'pr' program - GCC flags -W h␀␀␀␀␀␀     (already done)art@␀␀␀␀␀␀   patch - si no moleste the files in the spool queue patchtarH␀␀␀␀␀␀   - silly little kerberos include file patch - can't spell printerand>␀␀␀␀␀␀ Slew of patches sent in by Tim Waugh <twaugh@redhat.com>s␀␀␀␀␀␀e -␀␀␀␀␀␀    Craig Small <csmall@eye-net.com.au>)1␀?␀␀␀␀␀␀  (Spotted by the guy with the red pen and the eagle eyes:2␀␀␀␀␀␀ printcap.5 had :as and :ae examples reversedt␀␀␀␀␀␀PC8␀␀␀␀␀␀Version LPRng-3.8.10 - Sun Mar 31 11:31:19 PST 20021␀␀␀␀␀␀␀rv:␀␀␀␀␀␀  messages on STDOUT (fd 2) as well as STDERR (fd 3).␀C␀␀␀␀␀␀  such as pap from Appletalk seem to need this as they produceE␀␀␀␀␀␀  device, did not provide 'stdout' for the filter.  Some filtersdlI␀␀␀␀␀␀  The 'Printer_device()' routine, when opening a filter as an output L␀␀␀␀␀␀.n-␀␀␀␀␀␀   take care of replacing "\:" by a ":".␀␀D␀␀␀␀␀␀   the 'expand escape sequences' code would be called and would␀␀␀E␀␀␀␀␀␀   where it would be used was in 'filter' or other options wheretaI␀␀␀␀␀␀   appears to be broken.  The fix was to assume that the only places␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀  entries C␀␀␀␀␀␀  Found a very odd bug... the escape code for '\:' in printcap␀␀␀␀␀␀ t ␀␀␀␀␀␀   <elija